Stiff platforms of SU-8 photoresist were embedded via long serpentine interconnections of Ti/Pt metal film (Fig. 24a
                        ). After undergoing 1000 repetitive biaxial stretching/releasing cycles at 30 % strain, no noticeable changes were observed in the charge/discharge behavior. Upon attaching the entire integrated system onto the wrist of the author, the integrated strain sensor successfully detected externally applied strains and the arterial pulse. This was achieved using the energy stored in micro-supercapacitors (MSCs), charged with silicon-based commercial supercapacitors (SCs). Notably, this marks the first instance of integrating MSCs (Fig. 24b), the strain sensor (Fig. 24c), and Si-based commercial SCs (Fig. 24d) on a single, stretchable substrate. With this integrated system, the strain sensor can operate without the need for external wires or a connected power source. Instead, it functions by utilizing the stored energy of the MSCs, which are charged by the integrated solar cells. This innovative design showcases the potential application of the system as a wirelessly operated, skin-attachable health-monitoring system. In Fig. 24e, a photograph illustrates the integrated system attached to the wrist of a 30-year-old male graduate student using commercial Scotch tape (3 M), demonstrating the detection of the pulse signal of the radial artery under sunlight. Fig. 24 g compares the pulse signals of the radial artery for three differently charged MSCs: MSCs charged with (red) an external power supply, (green) a solar simulator, and (blue) sunlight, respectively. Essential information about the arterial wall, such as the stiffness of the aortic system, can be extracted by analyzing arterial pulse waveforms through pulse rate and pressure. photograph illustrates the integrated system detecting wrist motion. The top left and bottom right of Fig. 24 
                        f depict the flat and bending states. Tensile strain was applied to the integrated system toward the black arrows, in the case of its bending state. This wrist motion can be detected by the change in resistance. When the wrist was bent, the resistance increased from 134 to 145 Ω, then gradually returned to 134 Ω as the wrist straightened. At the points of tensile bending and during the relaxation process of the wrist motion, sharp peaks are observed, attributed to the viscoelasticity of the PDMS/Eco-flex composite used for fabricating the FGF strain sensor. Therefore, there is potential for the application of this stretchable self-charging power/sensor system in skin-attachable health-monitoring devices. With the deliberate selection of electrode and electrolyte materials, and the design of device architecture, Park et al [320]. demonstrated the fabrication of a high-performance flexible MSC. Through the vertical integration of a flexible MSC, a strain sensor, and a gecko-inspired adhesive into a single device, strains induced by bio-signals and skin/body movements could be successfully detected using the stored energy of the MSC while attached to human skin. For use in skin-attachable devices, long-term usage should not induce any skin irritation. Thus, adhesive effects on human skin were compared with those of commercially available adhesives, including surgical tape, plaster, hydrocolloid dressing, and PI tape. After a 6-hour attachment period, all adhesives, except for ours, left irritation marks on the skin, as depicted in Fig. 24i. The integration of the flexible MSC, the FGF strain sensor, and the GIA into a single device enabled the detection of strains due to bio-signals using the stored energy of the MSC without a wire-connected external power supply. As shown in Fig. 24(j,k), arterial pulse, frowning of the brow, and swallowing signals were successfully detected in this integrated system. The pulse rate of 100/min for a healthy female graduate student could be reliably detected. Moreover, as the Adam's apple rose and fell due to swallowing, the corresponding peaks were distinctly shown. All signals without the adhesive are more distinct than those with the adhesive, likely due to the physical thickness of the adhesive film. However, long-term usage without skin irritation could be obtained to compensate for the reduced sensitivity, which can also be improved by thinning the adhesive thickness in future work. Hence, the high potential application of MSC as an integrated energy storage device in a future skin-attachable health-monitoring system.
